                <fr:route>/matrix-001K/</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="Geometric intuition of determinant">Geometric intuition of determinant</fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>remark</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>If we look at a parallelogram in the real plane, then we can describe two edges using vectors <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\vec {v}=(x_{1},y_{1})]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\vec {w}=(x_{2},y_{2})]]></fr:tex>. Its area is precisely:
<fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[A = \det \begin {pmatrix}x_{1} & x_{2}\\y_{1} & y_{2}\end {pmatrix}]]></fr:tex>
This is taught to students in calculus. Similarly, if we extend our discussion to a parallelipid in three dimensions, we would have three vectors and the volume would be the determinant of the matrix whose columns are these column vectors.</html:p>
                <html:p>This intuition captures one aspect of the determinant, as describing the "volume" of a "parallelotope" (the generalization of the parallelogram and parallelepiped to arbitrary dimensions).</html:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
