                <fr:route>/matrix-001O/</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="Determinant of triangular matrix is product of diagonal entries">Determinant of triangular matrix is product of diagonal entries</fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>theorem</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter><html:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {T}=(t_{i,j})]]></fr:tex> be a triangular <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n\times  n]]></fr:tex> matrix (either <fr:link href="/matrix-000B/" title="Upper-triangular matrix" uri="http://localhost:8000/matrix-000B/" display-uri="matrix-000B" type="local">Upper-triangular matrix</fr:link> or <fr:link href="/matrix-000C/" title="Lower-triangular matrix" uri="http://localhost:8000/matrix-000C/" display-uri="matrix-000C" type="local">Lower-triangular matrix</fr:link>, it doesn't matter). Then the determinant of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\det (\mathbf {T})]]></fr:tex> is just the product of the diagonal entries:</html:p><fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[\det (\mathbf {T})=\prod ^{n}_{i=1}t_{i,i}.]]></fr:tex>
 
   
   <fr:tree show-metadata="false" toc="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link href="/alex-nelson/" title="Alex Nelson" uri="http://localhost:8000/alex-nelson/" display-uri="alex-nelson" type="local">Alex Nelson</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:date><fr:year>2025</fr:year><fr:month>12</fr:month><fr:day>8</fr:day></fr:date><fr:taxon>proof</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><html:p>The basic proof idea is to do this by induction on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex>. The base case <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n=1]]></fr:tex> is obvious. The inductive case requires a bit of work, but amounts to following the definitions.</html:p><html:span class="qed">∎</html:span></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
 
</fr:mainmatter>
